1. Momentum breakout scalp
You trade the break of a key level like premarket high, intraday high/low, or a clear resistance/support zone, and you want price to move immediately after the break. Volume matters here: breakouts are generally treated as more meaningful when accompanied by high or unusual volume. This style fits fast, directional markets, but false breakouts are the main problem.

2. VWAP pullback / trend-continuation scalp
Instead of buying the breakout itself, you wait for price to trend, then pull back toward VWAP and resume. VWAP is the intraday average price weighted by volume, so many short-term traders use it as a reference for trend and intraday value. This style is usually cleaner than pure breakout chasing because you are entering on a retrace, but it works badly in choppy markets with no real trend.

3. Range or mean-reversion scalp
Here you do the opposite of breakout trading: you fade moves into support/resistance and bet price snaps back toward the middle of the range. Support and resistance are commonly used as price zones where buying or selling pressure has previously shown up. This style tends to work better in sideways markets and worse when the market starts trending hard.

4. Order-flow / tape-reading scalp
This style focuses less on chart patterns and more on the microstructure: bid/ask behavior, speed of prints, depth, and whether aggressive buyers or sellers are taking control. The bid-ask spread is the gap between the highest bid and lowest ask, and order-book depth is one measure traders use when judging liquidity, though CME notes depth alone can be incomplete. This is one of the most execution-sensitive styles because tiny changes in spread, speed, and liquidity can change the trade quality fast.

5. Opening-range or news-reaction scalp
This is built around the first burst of volatility after the market opens or after a catalyst hits. You define a small opening range or key reaction level, then scalp the first clean push or the first retracement after it. The appeal is that volatility and volume are often highest around those moments, but slippage and fake moves can also be worst there, so this is the least forgiving for slow execution. The need for fast exits and risk control is consistent with CME’s emphasis that stops are essential for individual traders.